# new column of herOntPc
def herOnt(row): 
    if row.herPc != None: 
        return row.herPc 
    elif row.ontPc != None: 
        return row.ontPc
    else: 
        return None
ont['herPc'] = ont.apply(lambda row: herOnt(row), axis=1)

total kg in ont dataset: 58232907394
total kg in af dataset: 12350571449
af dataset is 21.21% of ont dataset

The afgifte dataset is significantly smaller than the ontvangst dataset - af is only 20% of ont. Here are the reasons why this is the case (I think):

  • the ontvangst dataset might have some repeated flows. Let's say 100kg of wood is produced by producer A, then is processed by processor B, and then is further processed by processor C. This flow is recorded as two rows on the the ontvangst dataset. So 100kg of wood in reality shows up as 200kg of wood on the dataset.
    • the first row is: producer A --> processor B || wood || 100kg
    • the second row is: processor B --> processor C || wood || 100kg
  • not all waste flows end up in the afgifte dataset - only flows that end up with non-waste processors show up in the afgifte dataset. So flows that end of in the incinerator, for example, don't end up in the afgifte dataset because incinerators are counted as waste processors as well.

So how should I map and calculate the producers, processors, and receivers of waste?

  • waste producing PCs are located in the 'herPc' column of the ont dataset.
    • However, there's no way of knowing if the waste produced is 'real' (waste produced immediately after use like municipal waste), or already 'processed' (waste that has already gone through a waste processor and is on the way to be further processed by another waste company).
    • Also, one waste flow could be counted twice in the herPc column, see first point in previous paragraph.
  • waste processing PCs are located in the 'herPc' and 'verPc' columns of the ontvangst dataset, as well as the 'verPc' columns of the afgifte dataset.
    • again, it is a challenge to distinguish waste producers and waste processors in the 'herPc' column in the ontvangst dataset.
    • also, could there be a chance that the 'verPc' column in the ontvangst dataset is repeated in the 'verPc' column of the afgifte dataset?
  • waste receiving PCs are more straight forward - they are located in the 'eaPc' column of the afgifte dataset.

Challenges for differentiating producers and processors Extracting waste receivers is very straightforward, but differentiating between waste producers and processors is more difficult, see paragraph above. In order to differentiate between waste producers and processors, we need to solve the following problems:

  • find out which herPcs are waste producers, and which are waste processors. One way to do this is to see if the herkomst name also appears as a verwerker in the ontvangst dataset.
  • make sure that one waste flow is not counted twice.
    • However you could argure that this doesn't necessarily matter if you take an 'industry' and 'territorial' perspective. Let's say that 100kg of wood is produced in postcode A, processed in postcode B, then further processed in postcode C. If you care about the 'processing power' of postcodes in the Netherlands, then you would want a record of both postcode B and C, because there were processors in both pc B and C, even if they were processing the same flow of waste.

# find names in ontNaam that also appear in verNaam 
ontOntNaams = list(ont.ontNaam.unique())
ontVernaams = list(ont.verNaam.unique())

ontDupNaams = []
for name in ontOntNaams: 
    if name in ontVernaams: 
        ontDupNaams.append(name)

perDup = round(ont[ont.ontNaam.isin(ontDupNaams)].kg.sum() / ont.kg.sum() * 100, 2)
print('number of ontNaams that also appear in verNaam: {}'.format(len(ontDupNaams)))
print('% duplicated rows by weight: {}'.format(perDup))

number of ontNaams that also appear in verNaam: 582
% duplicated rows by weight: 14.02

Here, we found that there are 582 waste producers (ontdoeners) who also appear in the ontvangst dataset at waste processors (verwerkers). But what does it actually mean when the same name appears in both the ontNaam and verNaam column? Are these names producers, or processors?

Here's my guess (see sketch below): companies that appear both as ontdoeners and verwerkers are actually verwerkers. They sometimes appear as ontdoeners because they sometimes give their processed waste to another waste company for further processing. So, in order to make a dataframe for processors, we just have to look at the verwerker columns of the ontvangst dataset. However, to make a dataframe for producers, we should look at the ontdoener column of the ontvangst dataset, but get rid of the names that also appear in the verwerker column. (image below gives a good summary of this)

Space-related data¶

Here we extract data from datasets about space, such as accessibility, density, proximity, urbanization. This type of data can be found in the following datasets:

  • Open Street Map (land-use)
    • km2 of industrial land in the neighborhood
    • distance (km) to nearest industrial area
  • CBS (accessibility, density)
    • population density in the neighborhood
    • distance from nearest highway access point
    • land value
    • distance to nearest urban area type
  • other sources (mymaps, other websites)
    • distance from nearest airport
    • distance from nearest seaport
    • distance from nearest freight station

Industrial land factors from open street map data

  • km2 of industrial land in the neighborhood
  • distance (km) to nearest industrial area

Here we add variables from the open street map dataset. OSM data can be downloaded easily from the following websites:

  • https://download.geofabrik.de/europe.html
  • https://extract.bbbike.org/
  • https://www.openstreetmap.org/export#map=9/52.0508/5.4959

%%time
# calculate km2 industrial land for each pc 
def indLand(x): 
    try: 
        temp = osm[osm.pc == x]
        intersection = temp.geometry.intersection(mp)
        area = intersection.area.iloc[0] / 1000000
    except: 
        area = np.NaN
    return area

osm = pc.copy()
osm.geometry = osm.geometry.buffer(0) # prevents self-intersection error
osm = osm.to_crs('EPSG:28992')
osm['areaIndLand'] = osm.pc.map(lambda x: indLand(x))

# add other params 
osm['areaPc'] = osm.geometry.area / 1000000 # total area of pc
osm['percIndLand'] = osm.areaIndLand / osm.areaPc * 100 # % industrial land for each pc

# display

from shapely.ops import nearest_points

# multipolygon of centroids of all industrial areas in nl
indpt = indland.geometry.centroid
indpt = indpt.geometry.unary_union

# find nearest industrial area (centroid) for each pc
def nearest(x): 
    nearest = nearest_points(x, indpt)[1]
    return nearest
pcpt = osm.geometry.centroid
nearestIndPt = pcpt.map(lambda x: nearest(x))
nearestIndPt = nearestIndPt.set_crs('EPSG:28992')

# calculate distance to nearest industrial area (centroid) for each pc
osm['distInd'] = pcpt.distance(nearestIndPt) / 1000
osm['distInd'] = osm.apply(lambda row: 0 if row.areaIndLand > 0 else row.distInd, axis=1)

# display
osm = osm[['pc', 'geometry', 'areaIndLand', 'percIndLand', 'distInd']]

cbs = cbs[['PC4', 'INWONER', 'AANTAL_HH', 'GEM_HH_GR', 'WONING', 'WOZWONING', 'AFS_OPRIT', 'AFS_TRNOVS', 'AFS_TREINS', 'OAD', 'STED', 'geometry']]
cbs.rename(columns={
    'PC4': 'pc', 
    'INWONER': 'population', 
    'AANTAL_HH': 'numHh', 
    'GEM_HH_GR': 'avHhSize',
    'WONING': 'numDwellings', 
    'WOZWONING': 'avHhPrice', 
    'AFS_OPRIT': 'kmMainRoad', 
    'AFS_TRNOVS': 'kmMainTrain', 
    'AFS_TREINS': 'kmTrain', 
    'OAD': 'addressesPerKm2', 
    'STED': 'urbanCode'
}, inplace=True)
cbs.pc = cbs.pc.astype(str)

columns = ['population', 'numHh', 'avHhSize', 'numDwellings', 'avHhPrice', 'kmMainRoad',
       'kmMainTrain', 'kmTrain', 'addressesPerKm2', 'urbanCode']
for column in columns: 
    cbs[column] = cbs[column].map(lambda x: np.NaN if x < 0 else x)

# POPULATION DENSITY
cbs['area'] = cbs.geometry.area / 1000000
cbs['popDens'] = cbs.population / cbs.area

# deal with na values
for i in ['population', 'popDens', 'numHh', 'numDwellings', 'addressesPerKm2']: 
    cbs[i].fillna(0, inplace=True)

# display
cbs = cbs[['pc', 'population', 'popDens', 'numHh', 'numDwellings',
       'addressesPerKm2', 'kmMainRoad', 'kmMainTrain', 'urbanCode',
       'avHhPrice', 'geometry']]

# DISTANCE TO NEAREST URBAN AREA
distUrb = cbs[['pc', 'geometry', 'urbanCode']].copy()

# create multi-polygon of centroids of different levels of urban areas 
urbMps = {}
for i, v in enumerate(['disturb1', 'disturb2', 'disturb3', 'disturb4', 'disturb5']): 
    temp = cbs[cbs.urbanCode == i+1]
    temp = temp.geometry.centroid
    urbMps[v] = temp.geometry.unary_union
    
# find nearest urban area for each pc 
nearestUrbPt = {}
pcpt = distUrb.geometry.centroid
for i, v in enumerate(['disturb1', 'disturb2', 'disturb3', 'disturb4', 'disturb5']): 
    temp = pcpt.map(lambda x: nearest_points(x, urbMps[v])[1])
    nearestUrbPt[v] = temp.set_crs('EPSG:28992')
    
# calculate distance between each pc and nearest urban area (dist = 0 if pc is already an urban area)
for i, v in enumerate(['disturb1', 'disturb2', 'disturb3', 'disturb4', 'disturb5']): 
    distUrb[v] = pcpt.distance(nearestUrbPt[v]) / 1000
    distUrb[v] = distUrb.apply(lambda row: 0 if row.urbanCode == i+1 else row[v], axis=1)

# DETERMINE IF PC IS IN FUNCTIONAL URBAN AREA
fua = gpd.read_file('../data/spatial-data/functional-urban-areas_nl/NLD_core.shp')
fua = fua.to_crs('EPSG:28992')

def inFua(row): 
    
    # find if the pc is within one of the fuas 
    inFua = fua.geometry.contains(row.geometry) # returns boolean value
    
    # find fua name 
    if inFua.sum() >= 1: 
        nameFua = fua[fua.contains(row.geometry)].reset_index().loc[0,'fuaname']
        inFua = 1
    else: 
        nameFua = 'notInFua'
        inFua = 0
    
    return inFua

distUrb['fua'] = distUrb.apply(lambda row: inFua(row), axis=1)

# DISTANCE FROM NEAREST FUNCTIONAL URBAN AREA
# multipolygon of centroids of fuas 
fuaMp = fua.geometry
fuaMp = fuaMp.geometry.unary_union

# find fua centroid for each pc
def nearest(x, mp): 
    nearest = nearest_points(x, mp)[1]
    return nearest
pcpt = distUrb.geometry.centroid
nearestFua = pcpt.map(lambda x: nearest(x, fuaMp))
nearestFua = nearestFua.set_crs('EPSG:28992')

# calculate distance to nearest fua centroid for each pc
distUrb['distFua'] = pcpt.distance(nearestFua) / 1000
distUrb.distFua = distUrb.apply(lambda row: 0 if row.fua == 1 else row.distFua, axis=1)

People-related data¶

Here we extract data from datasets about people, such as density, income or education level per postcode. This type of data can be found in the following datasets:

  • CBS (central beuraeau of statistics)

CBS Data

Relevant columns (see detailed explanations on CBS website):

  • PC4 - postcode
  • INWONER - num residents
  • AANTAL_HH - num households
  • GEM_HH_GR - av. household size
  • WONING - num houses
  • WOZWONING - av. household price
  • M_INKHH - median income per household
  • P_LINK_HH - % low income households
  • P_HINK_HH - % high income households
  • AFS_OPRIT - km to main road access ramp
  • AFS_TRNOVS - km to nearest major interchange station
  • AFS_TREINS - km to nearest train station
  • AFS_ONDHV - km to nearest havo/vwo
  • AV10_ONDHV - num havo/vwo within 10km
  • AFS_ONDVMB - km to nearest vmbo
  • AV10ONDVMB - num vmbo within 10km
  • OAD - num addresses per km2
  • STED - urbanity code (1=very urban, 5=non-urban)
  • geometry

  • kg_received, log(kg_received) - LMA data
  • space, people, and flow-related explanatory variables

# create df with columns: pc4, log(kg), cbs variables for each pc4
# read afgifte dataframe 
df = feather.read_dataframe('../data/lma/af_2019-2020_matched-codes.feather')
df = df[~df.gnc.isna()] # extract rows with gnc
df.eaPostcode = df.eaPostcode.str[:4] # convert to pc4 
df = df[df.year == 2019] # only looking at numbers in 2019
df.eaPostcode = df.eaPostcode.astype('int64')
df = df[['eaPostcode', 'gnc', 'kg']]
df = df.groupby(['eaPostcode', 'gnc']).sum().kg.reset_index()
df.rename(columns={'eaPostcode': 'postcode', 'kg': 'kg_received'}, inplace=True)

# create column with log kg values 
def log(x): 
    if x > 0: 
        return np.log(x)
    else: 
        return 0
df['log_kg'] = df.kg_received.map(lambda x: log(x))
print('afgifte rows, columns: {}'.format(df.shape))
print('cbs rows, columns: {}'.format(cbs.shape))

# merge with cbs data (which already has geometry)
df = pd.merge(df, cbs, how='right', left_on='postcode', right_on='pc4')
df.drop(labels=['postcode'], axis=1, inplace=True)
df['kg_received'] = df['kg_received'].fillna(0) 
df['log_kg'] = df['log_kg'].fillna(0) 
df = df[['pc4','kg_received', 'log_kg','gnc', 'pop', 'numHh', 'avHhSize', 'avHhPrice',
       'numDwellings', 'medHhIncome', 'perLowIncome', 'perHighIncome',
       'kmMainRoad', 'kmMainTrain', 'kmTrain', 'kmHavo', '10kmHavo', 'kmVmbo',
       '10kmVmbo', 'addressesPerKm2', 'urbanCode']] # rearrange pc4 in front, drop kg_received 

# display shape
print('merged (cbs+lma) rows, columns: {}'.format(df.shape))

# add geometry of postcodes to df
nl_pc4 = gpd.read_file('../data/spatial-data/nl_pc4.shp')
nl_pc4 = nl_pc4[['PC4', 'geometry']]
nl_pc4.PC4 = nl_pc4.PC4.astype('int64')
print('nl_pc4 rows, columns: {}'.format(nl_pc4.shape))
df = pd.merge(df, nl_pc4, how='left', left_on='pc4', right_on='PC4')

The first two rows of the scatter matrix below shows the relationship between kg_received and log(kg) (the dependent variables) with all other explanatory variables (such as km from main road, number of universities within a 10km radius...etc). As we can see, the scatterplots on the first row (kg_received) all have a similar shape - a downward curve. This probably has more do to with the log-distribution of values than any actual trends. The scatterplots on the second row (log(kg)) don't seem to be following any pattern - they are all blobs. This suggests that there are no significant relationships between total kg_received and any of the cbs data. There are two ways to proceed here: one would be to study kg_received of a specific material instead of all materials in general. Another would be to find other explanatory variables that might have a stronger relationships with kg_received.

Exploratory regression¶

Before doing a regression analysis, we need to choose the right explanatory variables. In other words, we need to choose variables that will more likely have a significant effect on our dependent variable, log(kg). We can choose variables by reading existing literature (we've made a start with our previous paper), but we can also do this using tools. One of these tools is the exploratory regression tool developed by ArcGIS. This tool finds a combination of explanatory variables that best explains the dependent variable. It does this by first finding the best variable, then the best combination of two variables, then three variables...and so on, until a passing model is found. Each iteration is evaluated using a number a statistical tests - AICc, VIF, JB, and R2.

Explanation of the statistical tests:

  • Akaike information criterion (AIC): The Akaike information criterion (AIC) is an estimator of prediction error and thereby relative quality of statistical models for a given set of data. Given a collection of models for the data, AIC estimates the quality of each model, relative to each of the other models. Thus, AIC provides a means for model selection. The lower the number, the better the model.
  • Variance inflation factor (VIF): The Variation inflation factor (VIF) checks for redundant variables in a regression model. In other words, it checks if multiple variables have the same effect on the model. As a rule of thumb, a model with a VIF of 7.5 or lower is considered acceptable.
  • Jarque-Bera test (JB): The Jarque-Bera test checks whether data is normally distributed (follows a bell-shape curve). For exploratory regression, this test is applied to the errors of a model to see if errors are normally distributed. If the JB is far from zero, it signals that the errors are not normally distributed, and that the model is inaccurate.
  • Coefficient of determination (R2, pronounced R-squared): The coefficient of determination (usually called r-squared) shows how accurate a model is, or in other words, how well the formula explains the data. The r2 number can be interpreted as a percentage - for example, a model with an r2 of 0.86 explains 86% of data variability. As a rule of thumb, models with an r2 > 0.8 are deemed as passing.
